8. Doctors Saving Jews in Dniepropetrovsk during the Nazi Occupation -- t19. Crimean Doctors: Victims of Holocaust and Heroes of Resistance -- t20. Jewish Medics in the Soviet Partisan Movement in the Ukraine -- tAfterword. The Ethical and Human Dimension of Jewish Medical Resistance during the Holocaust -- tPhotos -- tNotes on Contributors -- tList of Abbreviations and Acronyms -- tGlossary -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFaced with infectious diseases, starvation, lack of medicines, lack of clean water, and safe sewage, Jewish physicians practiced medicine under severe conditions in the ghettos and concentration camps of the Holocaust. Despite the odds against them, physicians managed to supply public health education, enforce hygiene protocols, inspect buildings and latrines, enact quarantine, and perform triage. Many gave their lives to help fellow prisoners. Based on archival materials and featuring memoirs of Holocaust survivors, this volume offers a rich array of both tragic and inspiring studies of the sanctification of life as practiced by Jewish medical professionals. More than simply a medical story, these histories represent the finest exemplification of a humanist moral imperative during a dark hour of recent history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xPersonal narrativesxHistory and criticism. 0aJewish ghettosxHistoryy20th century. 0aJewish physiciansvBiography. 0aJews - Medicine - History - 20th century. 0aJewsxMedicinexHistoryy20th century. 0aJewszEurope, EasternxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xJewish resistance. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xMedical care. 7aHISTORY / Holocaust.2bisacsh1 aArbus, Isak, econtribu